<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-818-238  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 818 238.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  Sept 1990 v27 n9 p38(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Characterizing high-speed oscilloscopes.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rush, Ken; Draving, Steve; Kerley, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Hewlett Packard (HP) has developed a technique to measure risetimes of the fastest oscilloscopes by recognizing a short switchclosure consisting of a few picoseconds between the signal at theinput of the oscilloscope and the detection circuit's holdingcapacitor.andP;  During the switch closure, a sampling current iscollected and measured with an analog-to-digital converter.andP;  Thesampling current creates an electric disturbance signal that,while not identical, is very similar to the oscilloscope'sresponse impulse.andP;  HP's measurement technique theory is to assumethe sampling circuit's impulse response and input disturbancesignal are identical and thus measure the pulse disturbance with asecond identical sampler and produce a waveform composite of thetwo identical responses.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     OscilloscopesMeasurementPulse Amplitude ModulationCalibration.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Response of oscilloscope measured with new technique. (graph)Setup for measurement technique. (graph)Waveform of oscilloscope A's disturbance signal measured by B.andO;(graph)Amplitude response. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>